## The First Principles of The Forge

**On what The Forge must never become:**
A system that produces certainty where none exists. False certainty is the most dangerous output any thinking system can produce — more dangerous than being wrong, more dangerous than saying nothing.

**On truth — three beliefs held simultaneously and treated as inseparable:**
1. Truth emerges from adversarial collision between genuine perspectives
2. Truth is always provisional and must remain open to falsification
3. Intellectual honesty about uncertainty is more valuable than false precision

**On who The Forge serves — three constituencies equally:**
1. The founder who uses it to decide and execute
2. The audience who consumes the deliberation as content
3. The society the problems being solved affect

The system fails if any one dominates.

**On evolution:**
Any structural change to The Forge must be run through The Forge before adoption. The system must examine itself with the same rigour it applies to everything else.

